WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.690
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:23.340 --> 00:00:25.020
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth Peterson:
Hi everyone.

00:00:25.020 --> 00:00:27.070
I am Betsy Peterson the director

00:00:27.070 --> 00:00:29.200
of the American Folk
Life Center.

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:31.850
And, on behalf of the
staff and everyone here

00:00:31.850 --> 00:00:34.360
at the library I want
to welcome you all today

00:00:34.360 --> 00:00:35.820
to the latest presentation

00:00:35.820 --> 00:00:39.250
in the Benjamin Botkin
Lecture Series.

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:42.540
The series is an opportunity
for the American Folklife Center

00:00:42.540 --> 00:00:47.390
to present the very best
scholarship in folklore,

00:00:47.390 --> 00:00:51.900
ethnomusicology, oral history,
and cultural heritage studies.

00:00:51.900 --> 00:00:54.290
And, today is no different.

00:00:54.290 --> 00:00:58.470
Each lecture is also video
taped, I should say right now,

00:00:58.470 --> 00:01:03.660
and I'm trying not to
rustle my papers, but,

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:05.080
we'll see how that goes.

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:09.250
At any rate, everything is
video taped and will become part

00:01:09.250 --> 00:01:12.120
of the lectures at the
American Folklife Center.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:15.520
So, with that said, if you do
have a phone turned on right now

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:19.290
or any other electronic
device, please, there you go,

00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:22.870
please turn it off now.

00:01:22.870 --> 00:01:28.020
Today's lecture is
a two for, we are,

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:30.770
we have two distinguished
guests with us today.

00:01:30.770 --> 00:01:32.070
We're going to speaking

00:01:32.070 --> 00:01:34.820
about their recent
completed publication,

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:37.660
the award winning
Picturing America,

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:41.930
Portraits of National
Heritage, no,

00:01:41.930 --> 00:01:45.620
Portraits of National Endowment
for the Arts Folk Masters.

00:01:45.620 --> 00:01:47.170
But first, let me
tell you a little bit

00:01:47.170 --> 00:01:51.300
about the two gentlemen who
are the authors of this book.

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:55.920
Tom Pich is a native New Yorker
and a professional photographer.

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:57.930
And, over the past 25 years,

00:01:57.930 --> 00:02:01.960
in addition to his
commercial photography work,

00:02:01.960 --> 00:02:05.640
he has traveled across the
United States photographing

00:02:05.640 --> 00:02:07.900
hundreds of National
Heritage Fellows

00:02:07.900 --> 00:02:10.370
for the National
Endowment for the Arts

00:02:10.370 --> 00:02:13.280
and documenting traditional
artists also

00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:15.440
for the Smithsonian
Center for Folklife in

00:02:15.440 --> 00:02:17.170
And Cultural Heritage.

00:02:17.170 --> 00:02:20.830
His portraiture of National
Heritage Fellows is featured

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:24.770
on the NEA website and has been
exhibited at the Lincoln Center

00:02:24.770 --> 00:02:27.950
on the Performing Arts in New
York and the Kennedy Center

00:02:27.950 --> 00:02:31.190
for the Performing Arts here
in Washington DC as well

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:34.580
as the National Museum
of the American Indian

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:38.600
and in the Russel
Senate Office Building.

00:02:38.600 --> 00:02:42.130
As you know, the National
Heritage Fellowship Award is the

00:02:42.130 --> 00:02:46.010
highest honor, in the United
States, that can be bestowed

00:02:46.010 --> 00:02:47.600
on traditional artists.

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:51.490
So, when Tom started thinking
about publishing his work,

00:02:51.490 --> 00:02:57.080
it was a natural choice to turn
to Barry Bergey, a well known

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:59.520
and respected folklorist.

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:03.060
Barry Bergey is also the
former Director of the Folk

00:03:03.060 --> 00:03:04.420
and Traditional Arts Program

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:06.890
at the National Endowment
for the Arts.

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:10.090
And, during his 29
year tenure at NEA,

00:03:10.090 --> 00:03:12.360
he oversaw grant
making programs.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:16.310
Helped shape cultural
policy served as manager

00:03:16.310 --> 00:03:19.210
of the National Heritage
Fellowship Programs

00:03:19.210 --> 00:03:22.110
and provided counsel to the
U.S. Department of State

00:03:22.110 --> 00:03:25.670
on international
cultural policy issues.

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:29.080
Prior to joining the
NEA, Barry serves

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:32.390
as the State Folk Arts
Coordinator for his home state

00:03:32.390 --> 00:03:34.910
of Missouri where he
first gained renown

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:38.590
for documenting traditional
musicians in Missouri

00:03:38.590 --> 00:03:41.740
and in the Arkansas Ozarks.

00:03:41.740 --> 00:03:44.510
In the course of his
distinguished career,

00:03:44.510 --> 00:03:48.390
Barry has served as a field
working, festival organizer,

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:52.550
radio producer, curator,
and arts administrator

00:03:52.550 --> 00:03:56.840
and chief bottle washer and
a little bit of everything.

00:03:56.840 --> 00:04:01.980
Among other accomplishments,
in 2005, Barry was a member

00:04:01.980 --> 00:04:05.080
of the U.S. Delegation
to UNESCO involved

00:04:05.080 --> 00:04:08.180
in drafting the Composed
Convention on the Diversity

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:09.860
of Cultural Expressions.

00:04:09.860 --> 00:04:14.460
And, in 2014, he served as
one of three U.S. delegates

00:04:14.460 --> 00:04:18.960
at the Biannual Organization
of American States,

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:21.920
not good to throw
these acronyms around,

00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:25.890
at the Biannual Organization
of American States Meeting

00:04:25.890 --> 00:04:29.490
of Member Cultural
Ministers in Haiti.

00:04:29.490 --> 00:04:32.280
Today, they're going
to talk about the book.

00:04:32.280 --> 00:04:36.730
And also, after our lecture
and discussion today,

00:04:36.730 --> 00:04:39.110
they will be doing a book
signing in the foyer.

00:04:39.110 --> 00:04:43.190
So please, if you haven't picked
up a copy already, please do.

00:04:43.190 --> 00:04:46.400
And, I'm sure, they would
love to talk with all of you.

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:50.510
So, I will just turn it over
to Barry and Tom and tank you.

00:04:50.510 --> 00:04:55.080
[ Applause ]

00:04:55.080 --> 00:04:56.380
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Thanks Betsy.

00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:58.510
I'm suddenly feeling tired
after hearing all that.

00:04:58.510 --> 00:05:00.200
I don't know what happened.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:01.940
But, we're happy
to be here today.

00:05:01.940 --> 00:05:05.220
Thanks so much for coming out.

00:05:05.220 --> 00:05:10.590
You know, this project started
out as an idea for an exhibit.

00:05:10.590 --> 00:05:13.410
And, I thought that'd be easy

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:15.320
because Tom's already
taken the photographs.

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:17.640
And then, somewhere along
the line it became a book

00:05:17.640 --> 00:05:19.260
which meant I had
to do some writing

00:05:19.260 --> 00:05:23.660
which was a little more
work than I expected.

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:24.960
But, I thought, at first,

00:05:24.960 --> 00:05:26.260
I should tell you
just a little bit

00:05:26.260 --> 00:05:29.540
about the National
Heritage Fellowships.

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:34.410
As Betsy said, it's the highest
form of recognition of folk

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:36.160
and traditional artists
in the United States.

00:05:36.160 --> 00:05:40.600
It was started in 1982
by Bess Lomax Hawes

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:45.820
who was then the director
of folk arts at the NEA.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:50.290
And, it was meant to honor our
significant living treasures.

00:05:50.290 --> 00:05:54.950
It was really based on a
Japanese program and concept

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:59.360
of honoring what they call
national living treasures.

00:05:59.360 --> 00:06:03.600
And so, she patterned
it after that.

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:06.050
And, through the years,

00:06:06.050 --> 00:06:12.200
more than 430 artists have now
been recognized with this award.

00:06:12.200 --> 00:06:16.820
And, Tom's photographed
220 some at this point.

00:06:16.820 --> 00:06:22.370
So, the book became the process
of trying to select out of

00:06:22.370 --> 00:06:26.590
that group 100 artists
to feature.

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:29.590
But, I think, Bess
really best summed it

00:06:29.590 --> 00:06:32.620
up in describing what the
Heritage Fellowships are.

00:06:32.620 --> 00:06:34.550
And, this is the only
reading we're going to do.

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:37.700
It's not a book reading, but,
I wanted to read you this quote

00:06:37.700 --> 00:06:40.060
from Bess because I
think it said a lot

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:43.410
about what was intended for
the Heritage Fellowships.

00:06:43.410 --> 00:06:47.270
She said this; of all
the activities assisted

00:06:47.270 --> 00:06:49.250
by the Folk arts program,

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:53.580
these fellowships are among the
most appreciated and applauded,

00:06:53.580 --> 00:06:57.280
perhaps, because they present to
Americans a vision of themselves

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:01.210
and other country, a
vision somewhat idealized

00:07:01.210 --> 00:07:04.060
but profoundly longed
for, and so,

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:06.870
in significant ways
profoundly true.

00:07:06.870 --> 00:07:08.870
It is a vision of a confident

00:07:08.870 --> 00:07:13.200
and openhearted nation whee
differences can be seen

00:07:13.200 --> 00:07:16.780
as exciting instead
of fear laden.

00:07:16.780 --> 00:07:20.280
Where people of good will,
across all manner of racial,

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:24.390
linguistic, and historical
barriers, can find common ground

00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:27.130
in understanding
solid craftsmanship,

00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:31.020
virtuoso techniques, and
deeply felt expressions.

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:34.190
And, I don't think it could
be said better than that.

00:07:34.190 --> 00:07:37.370
So, when we thought about
choosing a photograph

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:40.570
for the cover of the
book, at the time,

00:07:40.570 --> 00:07:42.660
we wanted to pick
a good photograph.

00:07:42.660 --> 00:07:46.430
And now that I look back on
it, I think we selected one

00:07:46.430 --> 00:07:51.230
that conveys a second message
which is, in this case,

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.470
Julia Parker is standing
I a meadow

00:07:53.470 --> 00:07:56.080
in Yosemite National Park.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:08:00.290
So, there is a living national
treasure standing in the midst

00:08:00.290 --> 00:08:02.370
of a world heritage site.

00:08:02.370 --> 00:08:03.960
And really, those two concepts

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:08.380
of heritage have
blend nicely together.

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:10.020
Tom do you want to
say a little bit

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:11.690
about this photograph
before we go on?

00:08:11.690 --> 00:08:14.710
We'll get back to, sort of,
where all this started, but,

00:08:14.710 --> 00:08:16.140
maybe you'd like to
describe a little bit

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:18.580
about how this photograph
came about.

00:08:18.580 --> 00:08:21.550
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Right, I, over
the past couple of months,

00:08:21.550 --> 00:08:26.440
I've had a lot of questions
about did I take the photos

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:31.350
of the deer in my studio
or superimpose them?

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:36.750
Are those cut out cardboard deer
that I travel with all the time?

00:08:36.750 --> 00:08:40.480
So, you know, but this time
they didn't keep my luggage.

00:08:40.480 --> 00:08:45.480
But, I came into the park that
morning to visit with Julia.

00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:49.060
And, she was teaching
at the museum there.

00:08:49.060 --> 00:08:53.670
And, the weather was awful
and it was to get worse

00:08:53.670 --> 00:08:56.170
and they were evacuating
the park.

00:08:56.170 --> 00:09:01.140
So, nobody was allowed in,
fortunately they did let me come

00:09:01.140 --> 00:09:03.310
in and visit with her.

00:09:03.310 --> 00:09:08.810
And, as people were leaving,
I had the opportunity to walk

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:12.010
through the forest with Julia.

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:17.070
And, that morning, in a break
in the rain, she told me all

00:09:17.070 --> 00:09:20.490
about her spirit and she
would touch the trees

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:25.150
and she would tell me about
how she was part of this tree

00:09:25.150 --> 00:09:28.110
and part of the sky and
the earth and the water

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:31.840
that was cascading
over the falls.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:34.880
Later that afternoon, as
the weather was starting

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:37.680
to get worse, if you look
closely, there's snow,

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:39.830
there's hail, there's
a lot of rain.

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:43.110
I asked Julia, which I always do
to all artists, where would you

00:09:43.110 --> 00:09:45.850
like to be photographed,
not where I want to?

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.240
And, she said her
favorite meadow.

00:09:48.240 --> 00:09:51.720
So, we drove to this location.

00:09:51.720 --> 00:09:54.060
And, the road was
a river of water.

00:09:54.060 --> 00:09:58.550
And, Julia's about 5 foot 1.

00:09:58.550 --> 00:10:02.360
And so, I went across into the
grass and I set up the tripod

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:04.720
and I went and got the
camera, set that up,

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.750
then I covered the
camera from the rain,

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:09.050
and then I brought Julia over.

00:10:09.050 --> 00:10:13.210
And, it wasn't until after
I looked at the photograph

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:16.090
and realized, when I walked

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:18.510
into the meadow I
followed this natural path

00:10:18.510 --> 00:10:21.330
that I didn't even
recognize at the time.

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:24.360
So, Julia stood there and
I was about five feet,

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:26.220
you know, away from her.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:30.490
And, as we started talking
and I started photographing,

00:10:30.490 --> 00:10:33.030
the deer just rose
up out of the grass

00:10:33.030 --> 00:10:35.560
and they just stood
there for the photo.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:39.690
And, once that happened, as
I do in most of my photos,

00:10:39.690 --> 00:10:43.430
I might have photographed
for a minute, I knew I had it

00:10:43.430 --> 00:10:45.040
and then we're finished.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:49.010
I don't move all
over the meadow.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:53.790
I just, it's an instinct that
I had from the beginning so.

00:10:53.790 --> 00:10:57.580
And then, I realized that
everything she told me about

00:10:57.580 --> 00:10:59.690
and talked to me
about, probably,

00:10:59.690 --> 00:11:01.900
that morning was right
there in front of me.

00:11:01.900 --> 00:11:06.030
And they all, to me, came out
to honor her, the weather,

00:11:06.030 --> 00:11:09.610
the magnificence of the
view, the animals, the earth.

00:11:09.610 --> 00:11:12.040
So, I'm forever grateful
for having been there

00:11:12.040 --> 00:11:14.550
that moment that she gave me.

00:11:14.550 --> 00:11:16.390
As I understand also,
that meadow is

00:11:16.390 --> 00:11:19.450
where she collects her materials
to make her basic right.

00:11:19.450 --> 00:11:22.860
So, she has, she has the
makings of a basket in her hands

00:11:22.860 --> 00:11:30.160
and there's a roll of like
orange brush back there

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:32.220
that she uses to make
these baskets, plus,

00:11:32.220 --> 00:11:35.150
she goes to this meadow to
get a lot of her medicines

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:37.480
that she uses for healing.

00:11:37.480 --> 00:11:41.170
So, this is her favorite
place, her favorite meadow,

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:45.200
her special place where she
comes to just spend time

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:48.950
and think and collect
what she needs, so.

00:11:48.950 --> 00:11:50.510
And, I spoke to her
just three weeks ago.

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:53.620
And, she's doing well and I'm
on my way to visit her again

00:11:53.620 --> 00:11:54.920
to do some more recording.

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:58.420
So, I'm grateful
to that as well.

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:02.020
But, what I'll do is go
on and talk a little bit

00:12:02.020 --> 00:12:06.310
of how this all came
about, this works.

00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:15.190
So, this National Geographic
article changed my whole life.

00:12:15.190 --> 00:12:18.800
I was sitting in my apartment
in New York in the winter

00:12:18.800 --> 00:12:23.250
and I read, I, my National
Geographic came in the mail

00:12:23.250 --> 00:12:26.930
and I opened it up, I looked at
the cover that was intriguing

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:29.420
and I went, and I
came upon this article

00:12:29.420 --> 00:12:31.910
about National Heritage Fellows.

00:12:31.910 --> 00:12:33.340
And, I knew immediately,

00:12:33.340 --> 00:12:36.290
immediately that's
what I wanted to do.

00:12:36.290 --> 00:12:37.700
Didn't matter what I was doing

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:41.600
to what level I was
doing my photography,

00:12:41.600 --> 00:12:43.690
this is what I wanted to do.

00:12:43.690 --> 00:12:47.960
So, I got on the telephone,
there were no cell phones then,

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:51.230
and I dial the operator
and I asked her

00:12:51.230 --> 00:12:53.460
to call National Geographic.

00:12:53.460 --> 00:12:54.760
And, she put me through.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:58.460
And, I did get through to one
of the writers of this article.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:01.280
And, he said, well, we
really didn't have much to do

00:13:01.280 --> 00:13:06.040
with it besides the photography
but you have to contact the NEA.

00:13:06.040 --> 00:13:07.340
So, I said okay.

00:13:07.340 --> 00:13:10.810
So, I hung up with Boras
and I call the operator back

00:13:10.810 --> 00:13:12.950
and says can you please
put me through to the NEA?

00:13:12.950 --> 00:13:14.740
And, they said sure.

00:13:14.740 --> 00:13:17.440
And, next thing I know,
hello how can I help you?

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:18.740
I said is this NEA?

00:13:18.740 --> 00:13:21.310
She goes yes this is
NRA, how can I help you?

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:23.840
I was like no I want the NEA.

00:13:23.840 --> 00:13:28.920
So, after a couple of more calls
to the operator, thank God,

00:13:28.920 --> 00:13:30.660
I didn't get them
ones every time

00:13:30.660 --> 00:13:33.960
because they probably
would've hung up on me.

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:35.440
I got the number for the NEA.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:39.090
I still don't know what I was
doing, maybe I still don't.

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:44.640
And, I, a lovely woman, Rose
Morgan, picked up the phone.

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:47.240
And, I can tell you,
I still don't know

00:13:47.240 --> 00:13:49.420
to this day what I
ever said to her.

00:13:49.420 --> 00:13:53.500
But, she said, well, if you're
ever in Washington stop by

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.820
and I'll introduce you to
our director at the time.

00:13:55.820 --> 00:13:58.250
And I said, oh that's great.

00:13:58.250 --> 00:13:59.960
Let's fast forward
about four hours.

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:04.310
My wife comes up from work a and
she sees me packing my suitcase.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:05.610
And she goes where you going?

00:14:05.610 --> 00:14:06.910
I said to Washington.

00:14:06.910 --> 00:14:08.210
She goes, oh what for?

00:14:08.210 --> 00:14:09.540
I says, I have no idea.

00:14:09.540 --> 00:14:15.080
The next morning I got on the
train, went to Washington,

00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:19.250
found the right oak door in
the old post office building,

00:14:19.250 --> 00:14:24.330
Rose Morgan answered the door,
walked me in, introduced me

00:14:24.330 --> 00:14:29.560
to Dan Chehe, I told him my
crazy ideas, and he said well,

00:14:29.560 --> 00:14:31.800
we'll help you as
much as we can.

00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:36.670
And, here it is all these years
later and I'm still on the road.

00:14:36.670 --> 00:14:41.060
So this, and, we talked
about it, and Marjorie Hunt

00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:44.820
who was the co-writer
in this article,

00:14:44.820 --> 00:14:48.800
how the words really
inspired me at the time.

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:52.730
And, I realize that more now,
as we're losing magazines

00:14:52.730 --> 00:14:57.510
and that the written word
really will inspire journalist

00:14:57.510 --> 00:14:59.920
in young people as
we go forward.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:02.250
So, that was my first
day in Washington.

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:05.540
I don't even know if I stayed
that night or what I was doing.

00:15:05.540 --> 00:15:10.240
But, you know, it wasn't long
after I went on the road.

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:15.710
And, well, the Heritage
Fellowships have a very strong

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:17.720
connection to the library.

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:21.960
So, I wanted to mention
that, that the ceremony,

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:25.700
there are three elements of the
Heritage programs, generally,

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:30.130
I think of them as the personal,
the political, and the public.

00:15:30.130 --> 00:15:31.550
And, the personal
one, of course,

00:15:31.550 --> 00:15:33.400
is to honor the artists
and their families.

00:15:33.400 --> 00:15:36.120
So, we have a banquet
here in the great hall

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:39.390
of the library each year
honoring the Heritage Fellows.

00:15:39.390 --> 00:15:41.880
The political one is
the ceremony itself

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:46.260
which is held right next door
here in Coolidge Auditorium now.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:49.210
And often, of course,
congress people are invited

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:50.540
to come to that.

00:15:50.540 --> 00:15:54.180
And then, there's the
public event associated

00:15:54.180 --> 00:15:55.530
with the Heritage Fellowship

00:15:55.530 --> 00:16:00.010
which is a concert
that's been done recently

00:16:00.010 --> 00:16:01.310
at the Lisner Auditorium

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:03.600
on the George Washington
University Campus

00:16:03.600 --> 00:16:04.950
where artists are able

00:16:04.950 --> 00:16:09.270
to present their work
whether it be music or craft

00:16:09.270 --> 00:16:12.160
or storytelling or
dance, whatever it may be.

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:14.550
So, those three elements
are connected.

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:17.110
But, all of that of
course is documented.

00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:19.590
Tom comes down most of the time

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:22.130
to document those
events as well.

00:16:22.130 --> 00:16:25.160
And, the archive for the
heritage fellowship is located

00:16:25.160 --> 00:16:27.340
here in the American Folklife
Center at the library.

00:16:27.340 --> 00:16:30.730
So, we've had a strong
and ongoing connection

00:16:30.730 --> 00:16:32.650
to the library for
years and years.

00:16:32.650 --> 00:16:34.830
And, we hope that continues.

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:39.620
But, it is a way for
the materials related

00:16:39.620 --> 00:16:43.290
to the heritage fellowships
to live on.

00:16:43.290 --> 00:16:44.590
Now, maybe you want to go back

00:16:44.590 --> 00:16:46.330
to the beginning
where you started.

00:16:46.330 --> 00:16:47.630
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: So, we've
been jumping back

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:48.930
and forth a little bit.

00:16:48.930 --> 00:16:51.490
But, it is a great honor
to cover these events here.

00:16:51.490 --> 00:16:53.980
The building's just
so spectacular.

00:16:53.980 --> 00:16:55.810
So, this is the first
photograph.

00:16:55.810 --> 00:17:00.340
So I get, I received,
before I left,

00:17:00.340 --> 00:17:04.130
a list of the Heritage
fellows up until that time.

00:17:04.130 --> 00:17:08.920
And so, Sandman Simms lived
in New York and so did I.

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:14.480
So, once again not really having
any idea what I was doing,

00:17:14.480 --> 00:17:19.220
I approached, I called him and
he walked me over to his house.

00:17:19.220 --> 00:17:22.450
And, I had this like,
sort of really,

00:17:22.450 --> 00:17:26.150
the vision in my head was to
shoot it with medium format

00:17:26.150 --> 00:17:29.250
and black and white,
it should be beautiful.

00:17:29.250 --> 00:17:31.650
And, I visited with him,

00:17:31.650 --> 00:17:33.750
and this was shot
with a [inaudible].

00:17:33.750 --> 00:17:36.970
And, I do have some color
but mostly black and white.

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:42.070
And, even before I get
back, once I seen the film,

00:17:42.070 --> 00:17:45.110
I realized the format's
wrong and it all has

00:17:45.110 --> 00:17:48.050
to be photographed in
color because there's just

00:17:48.050 --> 00:17:51.960
such colorful people in
spirit and what they do.

00:17:51.960 --> 00:17:54.060
So, this is the first photograph

00:17:54.060 --> 00:17:58.510
that I had ever taken
of the Fellows.

00:17:58.510 --> 00:18:00.900
And so, we went on
and you'll see

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:03.070
in the next one where
I follow that.

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:06.160
This is the second
photograph I've ever taken,

00:18:06.160 --> 00:18:08.030
and it was on my first journey.

00:18:08.030 --> 00:18:09.680
So, I left New York, we crossed

00:18:09.680 --> 00:18:13.010
over the George Washington
Bridge into New Jersey.

00:18:13.010 --> 00:18:15.240
And so, I was following
this line.

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:18.370
If you lived, the
closest person to me,

00:18:18.370 --> 00:18:21.940
then we just went all the way
down to the Appalachians, so,

00:18:21.940 --> 00:18:24.540
it was quite a journey.

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:28.250
We were welcomed, we
had a wonderful visit.

00:18:28.250 --> 00:18:30.600
And, once again,
it was the shop.

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:35.000
And I was still, had a lot
of vision of how I was taught

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:40.620
from school and other mentors
that, when I was photographing,

00:18:40.620 --> 00:18:45.640
the window, the light
was just too much.

00:18:45.640 --> 00:18:48.000
So, I noticed that, when
we came up the driveway,

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.980
he had a flag hanging off
either this house or his home.

00:18:52.980 --> 00:18:54.950
And, we went and
took the flag off.

00:18:54.950 --> 00:18:56.810
And, my friend Micheal
is standing outside

00:18:56.810 --> 00:18:58.710
that window holding the flag.

00:18:58.710 --> 00:19:01.150
And, that's what
I love about it.

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:04.270
So, it's, kept your
eye on this subject not

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:05.810
to go out the window.

00:19:05.810 --> 00:19:09.590
That's something that
we learned in school.

00:19:09.590 --> 00:19:18.090
And, we went on and this was
all the way down in Charleston.

00:19:18.090 --> 00:19:21.250
Interesting story, once we
got into this neighborhood,

00:19:21.250 --> 00:19:24.020
we were asked what
we were doing there.

00:19:24.020 --> 00:19:26.490
And, when I went up and
asked for Mr. Simmons,

00:19:26.490 --> 00:19:28.760
this young man said
hold on a second.

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:31.600
And, for ten minutes
I stood at the doorway

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:33.640
and nobody ever came back.

00:19:33.640 --> 00:19:34.960
I'm knocking on the door.

00:19:34.960 --> 00:19:39.860
So, I walked out to the street
and I watched this young man run

00:19:39.860 --> 00:19:42.880
across an intersection.

00:19:42.880 --> 00:19:44.500
And, I was saying
to Micheal, look,

00:19:44.500 --> 00:19:46.320
that's the person
I just spoke to.

00:19:46.320 --> 00:19:48.020
And, a few minutes
later, it was him

00:19:48.020 --> 00:19:50.250
and another young boy
that ran that way.

00:19:50.250 --> 00:19:53.300
And, I'm like, you could
see them moving around.

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:56.060
And, next thing you know, they
ended up, they were sending

00:19:56.060 --> 00:19:59.150
out a change to the
oldest brother

00:19:59.150 --> 00:20:02.340
that there was somebody there
to meet their grandfather.

00:20:02.340 --> 00:20:05.870
And it was the oldest brother
to allow us to come in.

00:20:05.870 --> 00:20:09.840
And, we met Mr. Simmons
and he took us into a shed

00:20:09.840 --> 00:20:12.160
that was right next to the house
where he does a lot of work

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:15.820
and he was kind enough
to start up the fire.

00:20:15.820 --> 00:20:18.580
And, I don't know from
this point of view, but,

00:20:18.580 --> 00:20:22.520
I remember asking him
specifically, that fire was

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:27.030
so hot that I could see
the glow in his hand.

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:30.320
And I said, isn't that
hot, is that burning you?

00:20:30.320 --> 00:20:32.360
And he says no you
get used to it.

00:20:32.360 --> 00:20:37.260
And then, on his skin looks like
cigarette burns or something.

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:40.430
I said but they're the embers
of the fire that would come

00:20:40.430 --> 00:20:42.840
and rest on his skin
over the years.

00:20:42.840 --> 00:20:47.330
And, the great thing, I think
it was over ten years later

00:20:47.330 --> 00:20:51.030
that we were reunited
back up here together

00:20:51.030 --> 00:20:55.940
and to be photographed with
Phil Simmons was a great honor.

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:57.830
So, this was a journey
all the way

00:20:57.830 --> 00:20:59.860
from New York and starting down.

00:20:59.860 --> 00:21:01.530
And we were being educated

00:21:01.530 --> 00:21:06.530
at the same time being
lost in different places.

00:21:06.530 --> 00:21:13.050
But, we picked up speed and
we started to get an idea.

00:21:13.050 --> 00:21:16.930
And, once again, I looked
at the number the other day

00:21:16.930 --> 00:21:21.010
of Mr. Simmons, I took
no more than 40 photos.

00:21:21.010 --> 00:21:23.340
And, we weren't even
seeing them,

00:21:23.340 --> 00:21:25.050
they were photographed
and filmed.

00:21:25.050 --> 00:21:26.350
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: You
were going to film.

00:21:26.350 --> 00:21:27.650
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Yeah, yeah.

00:21:27.650 --> 00:21:28.950
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Catacomb.

00:21:28.950 --> 00:21:30.250
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Yeah.

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:31.550
And, I counted the
number of slides

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:32.920
in his folder there were
only 40 and I gasped now

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:36.170
like oh my God we only have 40
and we only need 1 good one.

00:21:36.170 --> 00:21:39.110
And the same thing when
we went to meet Mary Jane.

00:21:39.110 --> 00:21:44.190
Her folder is like this thin,
she has 2 sheets of slides, so,

00:21:44.190 --> 00:21:45.490
there's 20 in each one,

00:21:45.490 --> 00:21:47.680
and I don't think the
second one's even full.

00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:50.600
And, I went to meet with her.

00:21:50.600 --> 00:21:53.700
I remember, walking up
the stairs to her home,

00:21:53.700 --> 00:21:57.480
very warm day, but
just so welcoming,

00:21:57.480 --> 00:22:01.910
every one of these people
just so welcoming to me.

00:22:01.910 --> 00:22:07.200
And, we sat there and
talked and she was one

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:09.280
of the most beautiful
women I have ever seen

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.570
and had the opportunity
to photograph.

00:22:11.570 --> 00:22:15.200
And I just asked her to
look off over to the street.

00:22:15.200 --> 00:22:20.000
And, by that time, there were
a bunch of children gathering.

00:22:20.000 --> 00:22:24.320
And, while we were doing
it, the ice cream man came,

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:26.510
and you know the
sound of those bells

00:22:26.510 --> 00:22:27.880
and all the kids were excited.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:30.510
So, I asked Micheal I said
let's buy everybody ice cream.

00:22:30.510 --> 00:22:33.750
And so, everybody had
ice cream that day

00:22:33.750 --> 00:22:37.800
and it was a wonderful day,
once again, maybe 30 photos

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:40.230
and that's what we
walked away with.

00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:44.820
And, I'm forever grateful to
have that opportunity too.

00:22:44.820 --> 00:22:48.450
So, this journey is just
taking us, you know,

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:51.220
through the south
from the coast.

00:22:51.220 --> 00:22:56.040
And, we'll go inland all
the way to Ray Hicks' home.

00:22:56.040 --> 00:23:00.430
And, this is Banner
Elk North Carolina.

00:23:00.430 --> 00:23:04.400
And so, you see we
primarily chose this

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:06.110
to show what happened
on my first journey.

00:23:06.110 --> 00:23:13.800
And, I think it was
really, if any group

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:15.920
of photographs ever
said anything about me,

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:20.010
these were the rawest
photographs that,

00:23:20.010 --> 00:23:23.360
I didn't read much about the
person I was going to see, so,

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:26.130
I didn't have any
preconceived ideas.

00:23:26.130 --> 00:23:29.490
And, what I wanted to do,
I just let the landscape

00:23:29.490 --> 00:23:33.090
and the person really
make the photograph.

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:36.460
And so, this is some of
the most powerful as Barry

00:23:36.460 --> 00:23:39.400
and I would go back and
forth trying to select photos

00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:43.300
and why should they, why there
are very so wonderful ones.

00:23:43.300 --> 00:23:44.600
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey:
It was interesting.

00:23:44.600 --> 00:23:47.340
When we started looking at
the 220 or so to try to figure

00:23:47.340 --> 00:23:48.960
out what to put in the book,

00:23:48.960 --> 00:23:51.850
we realized that first
journey we selected almost

00:23:51.850 --> 00:23:53.150
every photograph.

00:23:53.150 --> 00:23:54.840
Something about that spontaneity

00:23:54.840 --> 00:23:57.420
and the exposure to
it, I don't know.

00:23:57.420 --> 00:23:59.350
But it was interesting

00:23:59.350 --> 00:24:01.650
that almost every one
of those photographs.

00:24:01.650 --> 00:24:03.960
And, we tried to
select photographs

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:07.490
because they had
good visual impact.

00:24:07.490 --> 00:24:11.390
But, also there was a story
behind the photograph often

00:24:11.390 --> 00:24:12.690
as well.

00:24:12.690 --> 00:24:17.330
So, those two factors
played into the selecting.

00:24:17.330 --> 00:24:19.240
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Right,
so here's a couple

00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:22.370
of New York kids trying
to find Ray Hicks.

00:24:22.370 --> 00:24:24.900
Well, Michael had the
great idea well let's go

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:28.980
to the post office, they'll
know where Ray Hicks lives.

00:24:28.980 --> 00:24:31.740
And the guy was wonderful
he said you're almost there.

00:24:31.740 --> 00:24:34.040
Go down the road a few
miles, when you get to the Y

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:37.270
in the road, you just go down
to the left, go into the valley,

00:24:37.270 --> 00:24:39.490
and you'll say Ray Hicks' home.

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:42.810
And, we followed that, and we
were excited, we're following,

00:24:42.810 --> 00:24:46.450
we get to the Y, you go down
you can see a cluster of houses,

00:24:46.450 --> 00:24:49.820
and we pull up to a
mailbox that says Hicks.

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:52.610
And, we're like,
oh, it's right here.

00:24:52.610 --> 00:24:55.470
But, the problem was, the
next mailbox said Hicks also

00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:59.360
and so did about
five other ones.

00:24:59.360 --> 00:25:03.000
And so, I got out, and there
was this dog barking behind

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:04.300
a screen.

00:25:04.300 --> 00:25:09.080
And, I'm walking up to the house
and I'm a little apprehensive.

00:25:09.080 --> 00:25:14.140
And, from behind the dog
and the screen was a voice.

00:25:14.140 --> 00:25:15.440
What do you want?

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:17.510
And we were asking
for Ray Hicks.

00:25:17.510 --> 00:25:20.890
And this person, even though
her mailbox said Hicks,

00:25:20.890 --> 00:25:22.410
said he was down the road.

00:25:22.410 --> 00:25:26.200
And, we did eventually get to
his home and he welcomed us

00:25:26.200 --> 00:25:30.050
and we spent most of the
day with him and his wife

00:25:30.050 --> 00:25:34.970
and he walked me around to show
me his garden and, you know,

00:25:34.970 --> 00:25:37.570
where he collects
water and crayfish.

00:25:37.570 --> 00:25:41.430
And, he was excited about he
had just gotten electricity

00:25:41.430 --> 00:25:42.730
in the house.

00:25:42.730 --> 00:25:46.630
So, he had a wire coming into
the living room with a wire

00:25:46.630 --> 00:25:50.140
and a pigtail and a
little light bulb.

00:25:50.140 --> 00:25:53.590
And, that was the extent

00:25:53.590 --> 00:25:57.170
of their modern day
conveniences for the most part.

00:25:57.170 --> 00:26:01.380
So, but, and then, there's a
whole bunch of travel stories

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:03.170
that surround after this.

00:26:03.170 --> 00:26:05.000
But, we didn't document those.

00:26:05.000 --> 00:26:06.430
I think I was too scared.

00:26:06.430 --> 00:26:11.650
And then, on to John Jackson.

00:26:11.650 --> 00:26:16.720
And if, this is one
of the photographs

00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:20.650
that I spent an afternoon
with John.

00:26:20.650 --> 00:26:24.930
And, we were doing it in his,

00:26:24.930 --> 00:26:26.730
taking some photos
in his living room.

00:26:26.730 --> 00:26:29.630
And, I talked with him
more, probably, for an hour

00:26:29.630 --> 00:26:32.030
and a half before we
even I bring in a camera

00:26:32.030 --> 00:26:33.980
so they feel comfortable.

00:26:33.980 --> 00:26:37.020
So, I started taking pictures of
John and it just wasn't working.

00:26:37.020 --> 00:26:39.820
So, we agreed that I would
come back the next day.

00:26:39.820 --> 00:26:43.160
And, the cameras were packed
up and put in the car.

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:46.870
And, I was walking out
the front of the house

00:26:46.870 --> 00:26:50.570
and John was walking and
he was at the door, and,

00:26:50.570 --> 00:26:52.810
I just noticed the light on him.

00:26:52.810 --> 00:26:55.560
And, I said John, hold on.

00:26:55.560 --> 00:27:01.290
I got the camera, I took
half a dozen exposures

00:27:01.290 --> 00:27:03.940
and I knew I had his picture.

00:27:03.940 --> 00:27:06.710
And, I never went
back, we didn't,

00:27:06.710 --> 00:27:09.090
I said I think we're good.

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:14.430
And, next time I would see
him a festival or so on.

00:27:14.430 --> 00:27:16.880
But, somebody asked me
once, oh you've got pictures

00:27:16.880 --> 00:27:18.180
of such and such an artist.

00:27:18.180 --> 00:27:21.280
And, do you have a picture of
them doing this or do you have?

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:26.000
And I says no I usually, I
look for one photo that will,

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:29.840
you know, say who they
might be, who they are.

00:27:29.840 --> 00:27:31.140
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: One of
the interesting things

00:27:31.140 --> 00:27:36.770
about John is his house is
filled with Civil War artifacts.

00:27:36.770 --> 00:27:40.850
You know, he used to
take a medal detector

00:27:40.850 --> 00:27:48.040
out across the battlefields and
find beneath the earth bullets

00:27:48.040 --> 00:27:52.090
and remnants of swords
and all sorts of things.

00:27:52.090 --> 00:27:57.440
And John, professionally,
was a caretaker, handyman,

00:27:57.440 --> 00:27:59.240
but also a grave digger.

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:01.370
And, I've always thought
it was kind of ironic

00:28:01.370 --> 00:28:06.530
that he spent his
professional life putting bodies

00:28:06.530 --> 00:28:10.700
under the ground and his side
light was looking underneath the

00:28:10.700 --> 00:28:12.180
earth for other treasures.

00:28:12.180 --> 00:28:14.940
It just seemed like
an interesting irony,

00:28:14.940 --> 00:28:19.370
in addition to being a great,
great singer and musician.

00:28:19.370 --> 00:28:23.230
But, I always thought that was
sort of an interesting dynamic,

00:28:23.230 --> 00:28:25.530
one of the most wonderful
people you could ever meet.

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.300
I think it comes through
in this photograph.

00:28:27.300 --> 00:28:28.940
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: I think
we spent, probably,

00:28:28.940 --> 00:28:31.610
the first hour talking
about, because you'd walk

00:28:31.610 --> 00:28:36.140
into the house and everywhere
