00:30:04.450 --> 00:30:06.970
And I said did you never, did
we never show you the book?

00:30:06.970 --> 00:30:08.270
And she said no.

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:10.610
And, I went to this page
and I showed her that.

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:14.450
And, she goes oh, bluejeans
and a bluejean jacket?

00:30:14.450 --> 00:30:16.440
I says yeah, 1993.

00:30:16.440 --> 00:30:18.810
She goes, oh I wasn't
even born yet.

00:30:18.810 --> 00:30:21.150
So, I felt real good about that.

00:30:21.150 --> 00:30:25.350
But, these are some of the
other journeys and I'm grateful

00:30:25.350 --> 00:30:27.320
to have these photographs

00:30:27.320 --> 00:30:33.120
of realizing how crazy a
haircut I had at that time.

00:30:33.120 --> 00:30:38.580
But, once again, we
will welcome so much.

00:30:38.580 --> 00:30:41.630
We had dinners with both these
gentlemen and their families

00:30:41.630 --> 00:30:44.360
after we photographed them.

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:49.040
I don't think these, Canray,
the gentleman on the bottom,

00:30:49.040 --> 00:30:52.120
he had just gotten
back after being

00:30:52.120 --> 00:30:54.710
in the hospital for a few weeks.

00:30:54.710 --> 00:30:56.300
We went outside, we photographed

00:30:56.300 --> 00:30:59.000
for maybe ten minutes
at the most.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:03.620
Then he asked me to go dig out
some crayfish from the front

00:31:03.620 --> 00:31:07.380
of the yard so we
could have dinner.

00:31:07.380 --> 00:31:12.870
And, we did, so we
learned how to do that.

00:31:12.870 --> 00:31:18.710
And, once again, he was the
ending part of this journey.

00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:22.820
And we were in Eunice
with Boisec.

00:31:22.820 --> 00:31:26.160
And, we were out on his porch.

00:31:26.160 --> 00:31:28.150
And, a storm was coming in.

00:31:28.150 --> 00:31:31.350
And the midst the rain, the
midst of the rain started coming

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:34.500
through the screen and it
made him uncomfortable.

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:37.180
And, the light was
terrible, the lighting was.

00:31:37.180 --> 00:31:40.250
And, we went to his
living room once again.

00:31:40.250 --> 00:31:43.380
I asked him if I come
back the next day,

00:31:43.380 --> 00:31:45.710
if the weather was
better and he agreed.

00:31:45.710 --> 00:31:49.620
Put the cameras in the car, the
car was underneath the carport,

00:31:49.620 --> 00:31:52.800
tin, just a piece
of corrugated tin.

00:31:52.800 --> 00:31:56.040
And, as I was about
to get in the car,

00:31:56.040 --> 00:31:59.300
the wind was whipping
up, and I noticed

00:31:59.300 --> 00:32:00.940
that the rain was picking up

00:32:00.940 --> 00:32:04.870
and all the animals started
scurrying for shelter.

00:32:04.870 --> 00:32:07.480
And I asked him if
he would come out.

00:32:07.480 --> 00:32:08.780
There was a rocking chair

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:10.930
that was being moved
with the weather.

00:32:10.930 --> 00:32:14.100
And he agreed even though
he said he didn't want

00:32:14.100 --> 00:32:15.400
to catch a cold.

00:32:15.400 --> 00:32:19.160
He put on his jacket, put
on his hat, he sat there.

00:32:19.160 --> 00:32:23.160
And as I started taking
the picture, this rooster,

00:32:23.160 --> 00:32:25.080
or chicken, it's a rooster,

00:32:25.080 --> 00:32:26.960
started walking through
the frame.

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:32.420
And, I have six frames of this
photograph rooster walking

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:33.720
through, walking out.

00:32:33.720 --> 00:32:36.500
Soon as he walked out,
I knew I had the picture

00:32:36.500 --> 00:32:40.270
and I told him thank you very
much and we were finished.

00:32:40.270 --> 00:32:41.720
And so.

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:43.740
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Kind of
an interesting element

00:32:43.740 --> 00:32:46.880
of that photograph, behind the,

00:32:46.880 --> 00:32:48.300
the story behind
the photograph is

00:32:48.300 --> 00:32:53.150
that Boisec name is
dry wood in french.

00:32:53.150 --> 00:32:57.000
And, he got that nickname
because, as a young man

00:32:57.000 --> 00:33:00.020
when he worked in the fields,
when it started to rain,

00:33:00.020 --> 00:33:01.690
they always said he was
the first one to run

00:33:01.690 --> 00:33:03.710
into the barn to stay dry.

00:33:03.710 --> 00:33:07.790
And now, it turns out that Tom's
photograph was another attempt

00:33:07.790 --> 00:33:10.930
to photograph him and
avoid the rain so.

00:33:10.930 --> 00:33:13.000
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: He did, he was
very uncomfortable feeling

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.680
that mist coming in, and
then to get him to agree

00:33:15.680 --> 00:33:18.130
to step outside for this photo.

00:33:18.130 --> 00:33:24.640
And, it didn't take, out of
probably 20 seconds it was over.

00:33:24.640 --> 00:33:29.430
So, and we were glad that
the rooster decided to show.

00:33:29.430 --> 00:33:33.800
&gt;&gt; Barry Bargey: The rooster has
other functions in Cajun culture

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:37.290
