and it's funny because I know,

00:57:38.010 --> 00:57:41.650
when I meet with these
Fellows, they'll tell me stories

00:57:41.650 --> 00:57:44.810
that other journalists have
come to visit with them.

00:57:44.810 --> 00:57:46.660
And they've said, like this
one woman out in Kansas,

00:57:46.660 --> 00:57:51.490
it was like 100 degrees,
you know, I'm 77,

00:57:51.490 --> 00:57:53.340
he has me in the
cornfield then I'm

00:57:53.340 --> 00:57:55.580
in the hay field then
I'm holding this.

00:57:55.580 --> 00:57:58.090
I almost passed out
from heat stroke.

00:57:58.090 --> 00:58:01.860
And, that person didn't
even, they were just there

00:58:01.860 --> 00:58:04.270
to get the image and gather.

00:58:04.270 --> 00:58:07.170
And, I approach it
so differently.

00:58:07.170 --> 00:58:12.820
I spend a lot of time, before I
even break open the camera bag,

00:58:12.820 --> 00:58:16.050
I ask them where they
want to be photographed.

00:58:16.050 --> 00:58:18.400
I don't bring any
lights with me anymore.

00:58:18.400 --> 00:58:24.670
And, that came on the request of
my oldest daughter saying to me,

00:58:24.670 --> 00:58:26.580
she was in Puerto Rico with me

00:58:26.580 --> 00:58:29.180
and she said dad you've
just gotten so Hollywood,

00:58:29.180 --> 00:58:30.650
I had all these lights.

00:58:30.650 --> 00:58:33.600
By the time I sat them
up I've lost the mood.

00:58:33.600 --> 00:58:35.670
And, with some of
the elder people,

00:58:35.670 --> 00:58:38.050
by the time you put these
lights and the flashes went off,

00:58:38.050 --> 00:58:40.280
they were like, I think it
was giving them a stroke.

00:58:40.280 --> 00:58:46.750
So, I'm back to just pure
basics, what's there is what.

00:58:46.750 --> 00:58:48.050
I.

00:58:48.050 --> 00:58:50.930
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Yeah,
and I think, I think that,

00:58:50.930 --> 00:58:54.470
we call the book Portraits
because they are portraits.

00:58:54.470 --> 00:58:57.940
But, they're really a, what
I see as a collaboration

00:58:57.940 --> 00:59:01.530
between Tom and the artists
because they have some agency

00:59:01.530 --> 00:59:03.770
in the decision as
well saying well I'd

00:59:03.770 --> 00:59:05.320
like to be photographed
here or I'd

00:59:05.320 --> 00:59:06.620
like to be photographed there.

00:59:06.620 --> 00:59:08.740
So, I think it is a
collaborative piece.

00:59:08.740 --> 00:59:12.680
There's a great story
about Woolley McGray who's

00:59:12.680 --> 00:59:17.220
in the book Cowboy
Poet from Montana.

00:59:17.220 --> 00:59:22.060
And, he didn't want Tom,
originally, to photograph him

00:59:22.060 --> 00:59:24.450
because he didn't like
photographers coming

00:59:24.450 --> 00:59:27.480
to take his picture because
he had a bad experience.

00:59:27.480 --> 00:59:31.440
He was out on his ranch and
somebody came up to document him

00:59:31.440 --> 00:59:34.790
and followed him around all
day and they were ordering him

00:59:34.790 --> 00:59:36.320
to do this and do that.

00:59:36.320 --> 00:59:40.590
And, he was out in the field
throwing some hay bails off the

00:59:40.590 --> 00:59:44.740
back of the wagon and the
photographer said could you do

00:59:44.740 --> 00:59:46.040
that again for me.

00:59:46.040 --> 00:59:49.090
He said you come
back tomorrow at 11am

00:59:49.090 --> 00:59:51.110
and I'll be doing
the same thing.

00:59:51.110 --> 00:59:53.150
But, he wasn't about
to throw one off

00:59:53.150 --> 00:59:54.700
if it didn't need
to be thrown off.

00:59:54.700 --> 00:59:59.220
So, you do have that
conversation about things.

00:59:59.220 --> 01:00:01.270
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: So, Barry
sent me to the lions den.

01:00:01.270 --> 01:00:04.140
I go all the way to Elko Nevada

01:00:04.140 --> 01:00:08.570
and the first morning
I'm there I'm sitting

01:00:08.570 --> 01:00:11.160
in a green room waiting
for Woolley McGray to come

01:00:11.160 --> 01:00:16.860
and introduce myself and say
I'd love to get your photograph.

01:00:16.860 --> 01:00:20.070
It's 0 degrees out but I
want to get a landscape.

01:00:20.070 --> 01:00:23.660
And he was, he wouldn't
even talk to me.

01:00:23.660 --> 01:00:25.780
He's like why should
you take my picture?

01:00:25.780 --> 01:00:28.480
There's nobody else
better in Montana.

01:00:28.480 --> 01:00:31.590
And he went on and on and on.

01:00:31.590 --> 01:00:35.500
So, he finally agreed
not to beat me up

01:00:35.500 --> 01:00:38.270
and to let me photograph him.

01:00:38.270 --> 01:00:40.400
He said here's the deal.

01:00:40.400 --> 01:00:41.700
You can photograph me.

01:00:41.700 --> 01:00:45.780
Don't ask me to look at you and
don't ask me to do anything.

01:00:45.780 --> 01:00:47.080
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: So,

01:00:47.080 --> 01:00:49.730
he definitely stipulated he
wouldn't be photographed riding

01:00:49.730 --> 01:00:52.350
a horse as I can recall.

01:00:52.350 --> 01:00:53.650
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Yeah, oh yeah.

01:00:53.650 --> 01:00:57.930
So, I had this, fortunate, just
by fortune, the stage setting

01:00:57.930 --> 01:01:02.010
where he was going to speak
looked like an old town.

01:01:02.010 --> 01:01:05.670
And, the lighting guys, who I
had met, and we were talking,

01:01:05.670 --> 01:01:08.570
and we just put a
spotlight on the set.

01:01:08.570 --> 01:01:11.470
And, I put a chair, a
metal chair, I said,

01:01:11.470 --> 01:01:12.770
if you just sit there.

01:01:12.770 --> 01:01:15.480
And, it was an angle that I
shot it because he's noted

01:01:15.480 --> 01:01:20.320
for his red cowboy boots, and
he tucks his jeans inside of it.

01:01:20.320 --> 01:01:22.450
And, he never looked at me.

01:01:22.450 --> 01:01:25.690
And till this day it's one
of my favorite photographs.

01:01:25.690 --> 01:01:28.320
And then, Barry had
heard from Woolley

01:01:28.320 --> 01:01:29.620
after and what did he say?

01:01:29.620 --> 01:01:32.010
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: He termed
that one of his favorites too.

01:01:32.010 --> 01:01:35.000
He said something to the
fact that I never need

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:37.760
to be photographed
now I have this one.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:42.650
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: So, and he's,
then I stayed with him that day

01:01:42.650 --> 01:01:46.900
and he read this wonderful
poetry to the audience except

01:01:46.900 --> 01:01:48.650
for this one moment
when he turned around

01:01:48.650 --> 01:01:50.080
and said I'm a little
under the weather,

01:01:50.080 --> 01:01:51.900
this is after I photographed
him.

01:01:51.900 --> 01:01:54.620
Said, he was up all
night with a toothache.

01:01:54.620 --> 01:01:57.450
So, he turned around, and I
do have it documented frame

01:01:57.450 --> 01:02:01.590
by frame, turned around and
he pulled his tooth out.

01:02:01.590 --> 01:02:05.900
And, he spat blood on the floor,
took out a cigarette pack,

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:08.300
put it in there, turned
back to the audience

01:02:08.300 --> 01:02:13.850
and said I feel better
and continued.

01:02:13.850 --> 01:02:15.150
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Tough guy.

01:02:15.150 --> 01:02:20.090
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: So, everyone, but
I just let it happen, you know.

01:02:20.090 --> 01:02:24.510
But, and there is one other
photograph that I'd taken

01:02:24.510 --> 01:02:28.860
where there's a light reflection
from one of my flashes

01:02:28.860 --> 01:02:31.770
in a mirror to come
clean I left it in there

01:02:31.770 --> 01:02:35.810
because that's the
only one that I'm in.

01:02:35.810 --> 01:02:37.440
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey:
Any other questions?

01:02:37.440 --> 01:02:40.740
&gt;&gt; I can't imagine how
challenging it must have been,

01:02:40.740 --> 01:02:44.710
I can't imagine how challenging
it must have been to decide,

01:02:44.710 --> 01:02:48.610
you know, which people and
their photographs were not going

01:02:48.610 --> 01:02:51.320
to make the book.

01:02:51.320 --> 01:02:56.680
So, you know, was the
process you made a first cut

01:02:56.680 --> 01:02:59.750
and then did you swap
out different ones

01:02:59.750 --> 01:03:01.730
as you made your decisions?

01:03:01.730 --> 01:03:05.890
What was that decision
making process like?

01:03:05.890 --> 01:03:08.710
&gt;&gt; Tom Pich: Well, because
our families know each other

01:03:08.710 --> 01:03:10.010
so well.

01:03:10.010 --> 01:03:12.680
And, I mean, I was involved
my family in my process

01:03:12.680 --> 01:03:17.880
and Barry also, what we did is
we came up with our own list.

01:03:17.880 --> 01:03:22.410
And, I went to my
family and wrote my list

01:03:22.410 --> 01:03:23.860
and Barry did the same.

01:03:23.860 --> 01:03:26.760
We took those two lists
and we put them on top.

01:03:26.760 --> 01:03:30.290
And, about 75% of
them were the same.

01:03:30.290 --> 01:03:31.930
So, we knew those were in.

01:03:31.930 --> 01:03:36.560
And then, Barry took it
to the professional step

01:03:36.560 --> 01:03:41.330
of thinking geographically and.

01:03:41.330 --> 01:03:46.420
&gt;&gt; Barry Bergey: Functionally,
ethnically, different types

01:03:46.420 --> 01:03:49.890
of artwork, you know, craft,
music, dance, and so forth.

01:03:49.890 --> 01:03:54.590
So, tried to, I think
there are 45

01:03:54.590 --> 01:03:58.330
or there's 43 states represented
all together because we tried

01:03:58.330 --> 01:04:00.590
to give a broad sense.

01:04:00.590 --> 01:04:05.240
The real lesson, I think, from
it is that some folks would say,

01:04:05.240 --> 01:04:08.610
you know, this reflects
a diverse America.

01:04:08.610 --> 01:04:09.990
And, I think it does.

01:04:09.990 --> 01:04:12.540
But, 5that wasn't a
self-conscious decision

01:04:12.540 --> 01:04:14.650
in one respect and that is

01:04:14.650 --> 01:04:17.940
that excellence reveals
diversity as well.

01:04:17.940 --> 01:04:21.140
And, every one of these
artists is excellent.

01:04:21.140 --> 01:04:22.820
They are a living treasure.

01:04:22.820 --> 01:04:24.880
And so, it isn't hard
to find diversity

01:04:24.880 --> 01:04:26.180
when you look for excellence.

01:04:26.180 --> 01:04:28.970
Rather than going the other way
around, we look for diversity

01:04:28.970 --> 01:04:30.450
and then find the excellence.

01:04:30.450 --> 01:04:32.110
The excellence is there.

01:04:32.110 --> 01:04:34.300
And, I think it's
revealed in the book.

01:04:34.300 --> 01:04:41.040
So, the composite statement is
one, I don't think it's unfair

01:04:41.040 --> 01:04:42.830
to say it's a portrait
of America.

01:04:42.830 --> 01:04:48.860
It's not the portrait but
it is a portrait of America

01:04:48.860 --> 01:04:50.160
and we'd like to hope that.

01:04:50.160 --> 01:04:55.840
But, everyone also
had a striking,

01:04:55.840 --> 01:04:59.110
you know, image a good story.

01:04:59.110 --> 01:05:02.080
And then, we also in the book
put a quote from each artist

01:05:02.080 --> 01:05:04.530
so we could give the
artist's voice as well.

01:05:04.530 --> 01:05:11.570
So, every image also has a
statement from the artist in it.

